From BSP-4467:
{quote}
I can successfully login to my bamboo site x amount of times.. maybe 5 or 10? At some point, it will not allow me to fully login to the site. It will take my login and password and then sends me back to the home screen but I'm technically not logged in. In the upper right hand corner I still get the link that asks me to Log in. From this point I cannot log into the site, this was using Chrome. I switched to IE and it allowed me to login, but after x amount of times it start to do the same thing. The only way I have found to get the browsers to log into the site again is by clearing it's cache, cookies etc. Once I do that, then I can fully log back into the site. My guess is there is some kind of login counter in a cookie ?? that is doing some kind of check. Very odd bug. I'm running 3.0.1 on Linux. 
{quote}

Reproduced by *Marek Went*. Please, see more details in the Support ticket.

Setting a script abc.bat to be run with arguments "test" ""test"" \"test\" will make Bamboo run the following in the terminal:
{code}
abc.bat test test test
{code}

The problem also happens with arguments containing spaces like "-f c:\file repo\test.txt"
{code}
abc.bat -f c:\file repo\test.txt
{code}

Currently it is not possible to force a quote char to be part of the argument string or to use arguments with spaces.

Bamboo returns 403 responses when trying to access a REST resource unauthorised.  According to the spec 403 means: 
{quote}The server understood the request, but is refusing to fulfill it. Authorization will not help and the request SHOULD NOT be repeated. If the request method was not HEAD and the server wishes to make public why the request has not been fulfilled, it SHOULD describe the reason for the refusal in the entity. If the server does not wish to make this information available to the client, the status code 404 (Not Found) can be used instead.{quote}

In this case authorisation *will* help however so REST resources should really return 401 errors.
